               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CHAMBERS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">SHEA</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1361" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1361" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1361" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1361" type="given" value="EMMA JEMIMA"></interp>EMMA JEMIMA SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Henry Smith, a green-grocer</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183905130180"></xptr>
               <p>in the Borough. On the 30th of March, about nine o'clock at night, the prisoner came to my shop for a halfpennyworth of water-cresses and a halfpennyworth of pot herbs, and he told me to send half a cwt of coals to Lant-street—he gave me a half-crown to pay for what he bad bought, which came to 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I had not got change, and took the half-crown next door to Mr. Holloway's, who came back with me, and told the pri<lb></lb>soner it was bad—he said his father had taken it for wages, and he lived in Lant-place (he did not say the number) they left my shop to go there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1362" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1362" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1362" type="surname" value="HOLLOWAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1362" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HOLLOWAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a grocer. Mrs. Smith brought me a half-crown—I went back to her shop, and told the prisoner it was bad, and asked where he got it—he said his father had taken it in his wages, and had sent him for the cresses and pot herbs, that his father lived in Lant-place—I went there with him, and said to him, "This is Lant-place"—he said, "Yes, but I am d—d if I'll go"—he ran down George-street—I kept the half-crown, and gave it to the policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1363" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1363" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1363" type="surname" value="HUMPHREYS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1363" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HUMPHREYS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 127.) I was on duty in Fryer-street—I heard a cry of "Stop thief," and saw the prisoner running—I took him, and Mr. Holloway came up—I received this half-crown from him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1364" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1364" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1364" type="surname" value="MANNERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1364" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH MANNERS</persName>
                  </hi>. My husband keeps the Feathers, in Storey-street, Borough-market. On the 8th of April, the prisoner came for a penny biscuit—I served him—he gave me a bad sixpence—I said, "This is a bad one"—he said, "Is it?"—I marked it, and gave it to the policeman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1365" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1365" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1365" type="surname" value="GARVAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1365" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES GARVAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 44.) I was called by Mrs. Manners on the 8th of April—she gave me this sixpence—I took the prisoner into her parlour—I found on him a good sixpence, a penny-piece, two half-pence, and a duplicate of a handkerchief pawned for 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., which he said be got the sixpence for.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-1366" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1366" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1366" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-1366" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Inspector of coin to the Royal Mint. These are both counterfeit.</p>
